Aut trudit acres] The hunters encompassed some large space (gen- erally the scot of a wooded hill) with strong nets, which they gradually drew into a more and more nan-ow circle, while dogs and beaters with tort-hes were set to drive the beasts into a given spot, where they were attacked and slain; or else they were driven down to the nete, with which they were entangled or stopped‚ unless they contrived, as they sometimes did, to break through them, which would give occasion for a cliase in the open plain (sec C. i. l. 28).
